metadata.name: Floral H.U.E #1
metadata.description:
Floral hue is the delicate play of colors that exhibits the simple grassland during different seasons using the prism light refraction. The brush strokes background of colors and the complimenting imprints of the leaves gives the magical effect of nature that makes all the variations impressive. While the natural palette creates the seasonical view. The mixed color never fails to inspire with the variations beyond nature. 

The visual treat of nature accompanied by imagination would fade away the melancholy of life while placed as an Art piece resonating the pleasant mood of the creation. The light color pigments would create the morning vibes while the dark tints set in enchanting nighttime mode.

Floral hue is a sincere work to embrace nature and celebrate the gift of vision that silently creates everlasting memories of enchanting life. 

H.U.E - Happiness Unconditional Empathy

metadata.name: adrift #8
metadata.description:
Take your entire life, full as it is with the vastness of your lived experiences ‚Äì and shape it into your cupped hands. Cherish this mesmerising world of yours as you would a ripe summer fruit, and behold at a glance its delicate yet dynamic balance ‚Äî one change here or there, no matter how microscopic, affects the entire course of your world. 

How will you receive this world ‚Äì its situations that overwhelm, its sights that awe, the catastrophes, the serenity, its steadfast commitment to the present? Will you look upon all of us here, adrift and fragile together, with love?


Adrift is a project that reminds us to make peace with our world ‚Äì with all worlds ‚Äì by stepping back to make space for an all-encompassing perspective.


------------


Created by Jacek Markusiewicz @jMarkusiewicz
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art

Click on the image for resolution options and to save a .png file. Saving higher resolutions may not work in some browsers; in these cases, right-click-save the image. All drawing and geometric methods are written by mrkswcz using javascript, except for the following:

The pseudorandom terrain generation uses Hydraulic-Erosion by Sebastian Lague, inspired by "Reconnaissance" by TENDER x Nat Sarkissian (MIT License).

For finding paths that simulate connections in terrain and potential locations of cities, a C# script was adapted from the article "Pathfinding Algorithms in C#" by Kristian Ekman published in Code Project licensed under The Code Project Open License (CPOL). The code was translated to javascript and simplified for performance.

Many pseudorandom effects are achieved with perlin-simplex by David Guttman and seedrandom by David Bau (both MIT Licenses)

For more information, please see the bundle.js.LICENSE.txt file included in the package.

The "heat death" event is a small tribute to lunarean's fxhash project. The code that generates the disintegration effect interprets a fragment of lunarean's code. Further contributions are its adaptation for 3d transformations and its recursive character that modifies certain parameters over time.

The project uses CPU for calculations and rendering ‚Äì generating the image requires up to 500MB of free RAM. Testing was performed across browsers and devices, but please make sure it works on your device before minting. Note that there are minor colour-intensity differences between different browsers.

metadata.name: Ramble #37
metadata.description:
ram‚Ä¢ble - talk or write at length in a confused or inconsequential way / a walk taken for pleasure in the countryside

Ramble is narrative artwork about a life (or lives). From a single observation to a long history. Part prose part painting. After a time the letters of the narrative slowly cover with tiny abstract landscapes. They are the type of landscape painting you would paint on a postage stamp. As the size of the narrative grows it becomes harder and harder to read all the letters before they are covered. Eventually when all the letters are covered the landscapes are walked over and scratched. There is no trace of what was there to start.

Technical / Artistic

The prose is built around a slotted algorithm that builds sentences always starting with a universal pronoun. It then splits and randomizes the lines and fills the allotted grid space it is given. The build up of sentences creates a sort of character study or life.

The landscapes are a set of very simple rolling shapes with texture applied, they stick to a predefined color scheme chosen by the hash. They remind me of tissue paper stained glass kids make in kindergarten.

The scratches are just that, scratches or shapes that bleed through to the background. They serve to flatten and wipe away, chair scratches on a ballroom floor or bird footprints in sand.

---

Scaling the image up or down will yield slightly different final outputs. I prefer the 10:9 view ratio. Right click to save image. 

Just code (Javascript, no frameworks or dependencies).
Made by DSims (dillansimmons.com)
https://objkt.com/profile/tz1Q4YfANpgKAuPXd1fobzBzdjg6wtPmmw5m/created

attributes.name: Prose
attributes.value: They feared failure. They took a lot of drugs in college but turned out alright. They mistook weeds for flowers. They grew up faster than they would have liked. They buried the past or painted over it. They constantly outdid themselves, when it came to shrewd remarks. They gave it all they had. They wanted to be the best at what they did. They listened to Joan Baez. They ate raw garlic because their favorite writer said it would bring them health. They collected bad debts. They kept pets and talked to them in a baby's voice. They believed their country would overcome its problems. They kept inner monologues, they said 'For the love of God don't', but we ended up doing it. They chopped wood and ate BBQ. They built long lists of followers who didn't care for them. They tried to stay hopeful but boredom got to them. They started new lives. New homes. They wondered if their children would grow into weirdos. They watched tidepools glimmer in the sunlight.
